# Don Juan

For other uses, see [Don Juan (disambiguation)](/Don_Juan_(disambiguation)).

Don Juan in [Mozart's](/Mozart) opera [Don Giovanni](/Don_Giovanni), a painting by [Max Slevogt](/Max_Slevogt)

Don Juan (Spanish: [&#91;doŋ ˈxwan&#93;](/Help:IPA/Spanish)), also known as Don Giovanni ([Italian](/Italian_language)), is a legendary fictional [Spanish](/Spaniards) [libertine](/Libertine) who devotes his life to [seducing women](/Womanizer_(term)). The character has been a subject of fascination and inspiration for centuries, embodying the archetype of the charming yet morally ambiguous seducer. His story has been retold in numerous forms, from plays and operas to poems and films, each adaptation offering a unique perspective on the complex character.

The original version of the story of Don Juan appears in the 1630 play [El burlador de Sevilla y convidado de piedra](/The_Trickster_of_Seville_and_the_Stone_Guest) (The Trickster of Seville and the Stone Guest) by [Tirso de Molina](/Tirso_de_Molina). This seminal work introduces the foundational elements of the Don Juan mythos, including the setting in [Seville](/Seville), the key characters (Don Juan, his servant, his love interest, and her father, whom he kills), and the moral themes of honor, violence, seduction, vice, and retribution. The play culminates in the dramatic "last supper" scene, where Don Juan dines with and is then dragged down to hell by the stone statue of the father he had previously slain. Tirso de Molina's play has been adapted into numerous works, including the 1665 play [Dom Juan](/Dom_Juan) by [Molière](/Moli%C3%A8re), the 1787 opera [Don Giovanni](/Don_Giovanni) by [Mozart](/Wolfgang_Amadeus_Mozart) with a [libretto](/Libretto) by [Lorenzo da Ponte](/Lorenzo_da_Ponte), the satirical and epic poem [Don Juan](/Don_Juan_(poem)) by [Lord Byron](/Lord_Byron), and the romantic play [Don Juan Tenorio](/Don_Juan_Tenorio) by [José Zorrilla](/Jos%C3%A9_Zorrilla).

By [linguistic extension](/Synecdoche), from the name of the character, "Don Juan" has become a generic expression for a womanizer, and stemming from this, [Don Juanism](/Don_Juanism) is a non-clinical psychiatric descriptor.

## Pronunciation

This section does not [cite](/Wikipedia:Citing_sources) any [sources](/Wikipedia:Verifiability). Please help [improve this section](/Special:EditPage/Don_Juan) by [adding citations to reliable sources](/Help:Referencing_for_beginners). Unsourced material may be challenged and [removed](/Wikipedia:Verifiability). (December 2024) ( [Learn how and when to remove this message](/Help:Maintenance_template_removal))

In [Spanish](/Spanish_language), it is pronounced [&#91;doŋˈxwan&#93;](/Help:IPA/Spanish). The usual English pronunciation is [/ˌdɒnˈwɑːn/](/Help:IPA/English), with two syllables and a silent "[J](/J)", but today, as more English-speakers are becoming influenced by Spanish, the pronunciation [/ˌdɒnˈhwɑːn/](/Help:IPA/English) is becoming more common. However, in [Lord Byron's verse version](/Don_Juan_(poem)) the name rhymes with ruin and true one, and traditionally the name was pronounced with three syllables, possibly [/ˌdɒnˈʒuːən/](/Help:IPA/English) or [/ˌdɒnˈdʒuːən/](/Help:IPA/English), in England at the time and by later critics. This would have been characteristic of English literary precedent, where English pronunciations were often imposed on Spanish names, such as [Don Quixote](/Don_Quixote) [/ˌdɒnˈkwɪksət/](/Help:IPA/English).

## Synopsis

There have been many versions of the Don Juan story, but the basic outline remains the same: Don Juan is a wealthy [Andalusian](/Andalusians) [libertine](/Libertine) who devotes his life to seducing women. He takes great pride in his ability to seduce women of all ages and stations in life, and he often disguises himself and assumes other identities in order to seduce women. The aphorism that Don Juan lives by is: "Tan largo me lo fiáis" (translated as "What a long term you are giving me!" [1]). This is his way of indicating that he is young and that death is still distant—he thinks he has plenty of time to repent later for his sins. [2]

His life is also punctuated with violence and gambling, and in most versions he kills a man: Don Gonzalo (the Commendatore), the father of Doña Ana, a girl he has seduced. This murder leads to the famous "last supper" scene, where Don Juan invites a statue of Don Gonzalo to dinner. There are different versions of the outcome: in some versions Don Juan dies, having been denied salvation by God; in other versions he willingly goes to [Hell](/Hell), having refused to repent; in some versions Don Juan asks for and receives a divine pardon.

## Earliest Written Version

The first written version of the Don Juan story was a play, [El burlador de Sevilla y convidado de piedra](/The_Trickster_of_Seville_and_the_Stone_Guest) (The Trickster of Seville and the Stone Guest), published in [Spain](/Spain) around 1630 by [Tirso de Molina](/Tirso_de_Molina) ([pen name](/Pen_name) of [Gabriel Téllez](/Gabriel_T%C3%A9llez)). [3]

In Tirso de Molina's version, Don Juan is portrayed as an evil man who seduces women thanks to his ability to manipulate language and disguise his appearance. This is a demonic attribute, since the [devil](/Devil) is known for shape-shifting or taking other peoples' forms. [2] In fact, Tirso's play has a clear moralizing intention. Tirso felt that young people were throwing their lives away, because they believed that as long as they made an [Act of Contrition](/Act_of_Contrition) before they died, they would automatically receive God's forgiveness for all the wrongs they had done, and enter into heaven. Tirso's play argues in contrast that there is a penalty for sin, and there are even [unforgivable sins](/Eternal_sin). The devil himself, who is identified with Don Juan as a shape-shifter and a "man without a name", cannot escape eternal punishment for his unforgivable sins. As in a medieval [Danse Macabre](/Danse_Macabre), death makes us all equal in that we all must face eternal judgment. [2] Tirso de Molina's theological perspective is quite apparent through the dreadful ending of his play. [2]

Another aspect of Tirso's play is the cultural importance of honor in Spain of the [golden age](/Spanish_Golden_Age). This was particularly focused on women's sexual behavior, in that if a woman did not remain [chaste](/Chastity) until marriage, her whole family's honor would be devalued. [4] [2]

## Later Versions

The original play was written in the [Spanish Golden Age](/Spanish_Golden_Age) according to its beliefs and ideals. But as time passed, the story was translated into other languages, and it was adapted to accommodate cultural changes. [3]

Other well-known versions of Don Juan are [Molière](/Moli%C3%A8re)'s play [Dom Juan ou le Festin de pierre](/Dom_Juan) (1665), [Antonio de Zamora](/Antonio_de_Zamora)'s play No hay plazo que no se cumpla, ni deuda que no se pague, y Convidado de piedra (1722), [Goldoni](/Carlo_Goldoni)'s play Don Giovanni Tenorio (1735), [José de Espronceda](/Jos%C3%A9_de_Espronceda)'s poem [El estudiante de Salamanca](/El_estudiante_de_Salamanca) (1840), and [José Zorrilla](/Jos%C3%A9_Zorrilla)'s romantic play [Don Juan Tenorio](/Don_Juan_Tenorio) (1844). Don Juan Tenorio is still performed throughout the Spanish-speaking world on 2 November ("[All Souls Day](/All_Souls_Day)", the [Day of the Dead](/Day_of_the_Dead)).

Mozart's opera [Don Giovanni](/Don_Giovanni) has been called "the opera of all operas". [5] First performed in Prague in 1787, it inspired works by [E. T. A. Hoffmann](/E._T._A._Hoffmann), [Alexander Pushkin](/Alexander_Pushkin), [Søren Kierkegaard](/S%C3%B8ren_Kierkegaard), [George Bernard Shaw](/George_Bernard_Shaw), and [Albert Camus](/Albert_Camus). The critic [Charles Rosen](/Charles_Rosen) analyzes the appeal of Mozart's opera in terms of "the seductive physical power" of a music linked with [libertinism](/Libertine), political fervor, and incipient [Romanticism](/Romanticism). [6] After seeing a performance of Mozart's opera, Pushkin wrote a story in the form of a play, not intended for the stage, "[The Stone Guest](/The_Stone_Guest_(play))" (Каменный гость) in a series "The Little Tragedies" (1830). [Alexander Dargomyzhsky](/Alexander_Dargomyzhsky) composed an opera using the exact text of Pushkin for the libretto (unfinished at the composer's death 1869, completed by [César Cui](/C%C3%A9sar_Cui), 1872).

The first English version of Don Juan was [The Libertine](/The_Libertine_(play)) (1676) by [Thomas Shadwell](/Thomas_Shadwell). A revival of this play in 1692 included songs and dramatic scenes with music by [Henry Purcell](/Henry_Purcell). Another well-known English version is [Lord Byron](/Lord_Byron)'s epic poem [Don Juan](/Don_Juan_(poem)) (1821).

Don Juans Ende, a play derived from an unfinished 1844 retelling of the tale by poet [Nikolaus Lenau](/Nikolaus_Lenau), inspired [Richard Strauss](/Richard_Strauss)'s orchestral tone poem [Don Juan](/Don_Juan_(Strauss)). [7] This piece premiered on 11 November 1889, in [Weimar, Germany](/Weimar), where Strauss served as Court [Kapellmeister](/Kapellmeister) and conducted the orchestra of the Weimar Opera. In Lenau's version of the story, Don Juan's promiscuity springs from his determination to find the ideal woman. Despairing of ever finding her, he ultimately surrenders to melancholy and wills his own death. [8]

In the film [Adventures of Don Juan](/Adventures_of_Don_Juan) starring [Errol Flynn](/Errol_Flynn) (1948), Don Juan is a swashbuckling lover of women who also fights against the forces of evil.

In 1951 the [Brazilian](/Brazil) writer [Guilherme Figueiredo](/Guilherme_Figueiredo) wrote a play entitled Don Juan. [9]

In 1952, the [Spanish](/Spain) writer [Jacinto Benavente](/Jacinto_Benavente) published his play Ha llegado Don Juan. [10]

The Spanish writer [Gonzalo Torrente Ballester](/Gonzalo_Torrente_Ballester) told his version of the legend in the 1963 novel [Don Juan](/Don_Juan_(novel)). [11]

Don Juan in Tallinn (1971) is an Estonian film version based on a play by Samuil Aljošin. In this version, Don Juan is a woman dressed in men's clothes. She is accompanied by her servant Florestino on her adventure in [Tallinn](/Tallinn), the capital of Estonia. [12]

In [Don Juan, or If Don Juan Were a Woman](/Don_Juan,_or_If_Don_Juan_Were_a_Woman) (1973), a French-Italian co-production, [Brigitte Bardot](/Brigitte_Bardot) plays a female version of the character. [13]

[Don Juan DeMarco](/Don_Juan_DeMarco) (1995), starring [Johnny Depp](/Johnny_Depp) and [Marlon Brando](/Marlon_Brando), is a film in which a mental patient is convinced he is Don Juan, and retells his life story to a psychiatrist.

[Don Jon](/Don_Jon) (2013), a film set in [New Jersey](/New_Jersey) of the 21st century, features an attractive young man whose addiction to online pornography is compared to his girlfriend's consumerism.

## Cultural Influence

Portrait of [Wilhelm Troszel](/Wilhelm_Troszel) as Don Juan, by [Józef Simmler](/J%C3%B3zef_Simmler), 1846
Monument to Don Juan Tenorio in [Dos Hermanas](/Dos_Hermanas), [Seville](/Province_of_Seville)

Don Juan fascinated the 19th-century English novelist [Jane Austen](/Jane_Austen): "I have seen nobody on the stage who has been a more interesting Character than that compound of Cruelty and Lust". [14]

The Danish philosopher [Søren Kierkegaard](/S%C3%B8ren_Kierkegaard) discussed Mozart's version of the Don Juan story at length in his 1843 treatise [Either/Or](/Either/Or_(Kierkegaard_book)). [15]

In 1901, Finnish composer [Jean Sibelius](/Jean_Sibelius) wrote the second [movement](/Movement_(music)) of his [second symphony](/Symphony_No._2_(Sibelius)) based on the climax of Don Juan. The piece begins with a representation of Death walking up the road to Don Juan's house, where Don Juan pleads with Death to let him live. Also, the 1905 novel [The Song of the Blood-Red Flower](/The_Song_of_the_Blood-Red_Flower) by the Finnish author [Johannes Linnankoski](/Johannes_Linnankoski) has been influenced by Don Juan along the protagonist of the story.

The protagonist of Shaw's 1903 [Man and Superman](/Man_and_Superman) is a modern-day Don Juan named not Juan Tenorio but John Tanner. The actor playing Tanner morphs into his model in the mammoth third act, usually called Don Juan in Hell and often produced as a separate play due to its length. In it, Don Juan (played by Charles Boyer in a noted 1950s recording) exchanges philosophical barbs with the devil (Charles Laughton).

In 1911, Ukrainian writer [Lesya Ukrainka](/Lesya_Ukrainka) wrote poetic drama The Stone Host about Don Juan. As the author herself determined, [citation needed] it's about the victory of the conservative principle [clarification needed] over the split soul of Donna Anna, and through her – over Don Juan. The traditional seducer of women became a victim of the woman who had broken his will.

In Spain, the first three decades of the twentieth century saw more cultural fervor surrounding the Don Juan figure than perhaps any other period. In one of the most provocative pieces to be published, the endocrinologist [Gregorio Marañón](/Gregorio_Mara%C3%B1%C3%B3n) argued that, far from the paragon of masculinity he was often assumed to be, Don Juan actually suffered from an arrested psychosexual development. [16]

During the [1918 influenza epidemic](/1918_flu_pandemic) in Spain, the figure of Don Juan served as a metaphor for the flu microbe. [17]

The mid-20th-century French author [Albert Camus](/Albert_Camus) referred to Don Juan in his 1942 essay [The Myth of Sisyphus](/The_Myth_of_Sisyphus). Camus describes Don Juan as an example of an "absurd hero", as he maintains a reckless abandon in his approach to love. His seductive lifestyle "brings with it all the faces in the world, and its tremor comes from the fact that it knows itself to be mortal". He "multiplies what he cannot unify... It is his way of giving and vivifying". [18]

In the 1956 [Buddy Holly](/Buddy_Holly) single "Modern Don Juan", the singer gains a reputation for being like the libertine in his pursuit of a romantic relationship.

Swedish film director [Ingmar Bergman](/Ingmar_Bergman) wrote and directed a comic [sequel](/Sequel) in 1960 titled [The Devil's Eye](/The_Devil%27s_Eye) in which Don Juan, accompanied by his servant, is sent from [Hell](/Hell) to contemporary [Sweden](/Sweden) to seduce a young woman before her marriage.

[Anthony Powell](/Anthony_Powell) in his 1960 novel [Casanova's Chinese Restaurant](/Casanova%27s_Chinese_Restaurant) contrasts Don Juan, who "merely liked power" and "obviously did not know what sensuality was", with [Casanova](/Casanova), who "undoubtedly had his sensuous moments". [19] [Stefan Zweig](/Stefan_Zweig) observes the same difference between both characters in his biography of "Casanova". [20]

In 1970, Faroese author William Heinesen released his short story "Don Juan fra Tranhuset", in which a character embodying Don Juan is washed up on the Faroe Islands in Torshavn and begins to seduce the women of that town.

In the 1910 French novel [The Phantom of the Opera](/The_Phantom_of_the_Opera_(novel)) by [Gaston Leroux](/Gaston_Leroux), the titular character (also known as Erik) had spent much of his life writing an opera, [Don Juan Triumphant](/Don_Juan_Triumphant), refusing to play it for [Christine Daaé](/Christine_Daa%C3%A9) and telling her that it was unlike any music she ever heard and that when it was complete, he would die with it, never sharing it with mankind. Following the unmasking scene, Erik refers to himself as Don Juan as he confronts Christine, verbally and physically abusing her as he uses her hands to gouge his face, exclaiming "When a woman has seen me – as you have – she becomes mine... I'm a real Don Juan... Look at me! I'm Don Juan Triumphant!"

Don Juan is also a plot point in [Susan Kay](/Susan_Kay)'s novel [Phantom](/Phantom_(Kay_novel)), which expands on [Gaston Leroux](/Gaston_Leroux)'s novel [The Phantom of the Opera](/The_Phantom_of_the_Opera_(novel)). The titular character was referred to as "Don Juan" in his childhood, a nickname given to him by Javert, a man who exploited Erik as a child. Later in life, he began writing Don Juan Triumphant, spending decades on the piece, which [Christine Daaé](/Christine_Daa%C3%A9) heard after hiding in her room after removing Erik's mask.

In the [1986 Broadway musical adaptation](/The_Phantom_of_the_Opera_(1986_musical)) of [Gaston Leroux](/Gaston_Leroux)'s 1910 [The Phantom of the Opera](/The_Phantom_of_the_Opera_(novel)), the character of the Phantom writes an opera based on the legend of Don Juan called [Don Juan Triumphant](/Don_Juan_Triumphant).

Don Juan is mentioned in the 1980 [Broadway musical adaptation](/Les_Mis%C3%A9rables_(musical)) of [Victor Hugo](/Victor_Hugo)'s 1862 novel [Les Misérables](/Les_Mis%C3%A9rables), in which the character [Grantaire](/Grantaire) states that [Marius Pontmercy](/Marius_Pontmercy) is acting like Don Juan.

The former Thai Queen [Sirikit](/Sirikit) once told reporters that her son Crown Prince [Vajiralongkorn](/Vajiralongkorn), now King Rama X, was "a bit of a Don Juan".

Don Juan is referenced in Star Trek the Original Series, season one episode 16 "Shore Leave".

"Don Juan" is [Cockney rhyming slang](/Cockney_rhyming_slang) for a 2:1 degree classification. [21]

Rapper [Future](/Future_(rapper)) referenced Don Juan in the title and lyrics of his song Magic Don Juan (Princess Diana) on his 2024 album [We Don't Trust You](/We_Don%27t_Trust_You).

## Folkloristics

In [folklore studies](/Folklore_studies), the theme of a human living recklessly inviting a dead person or skull for dinner is classified in the [Aarne-Thompson-Uther Index](/Aarne-Thompson-Uther_Index) as ATU 470A, "The Offended Skull". [22] [23]

